 "text": "This is one single Chinese character, it has around 58 strokes, it means one specific kind of noodle. And until 20-20, no computer on earth could type it. Meet Bian. Most Chinese characters have a handful of strokes, 5, 10, maybe 15. This one crams nearly 60 strokes into a single character, it's so packed it looks less like writing and more like a tiny painting. And after all that complexity, it means… Just one thing, Bian Bian noodles, a thick, hand pulled noodle from the Shanxi region of China. That's it, one of the most complicated characters ever for one bowl of food. It doesn't even appear in standard dictionaries. As the story goes, it was dreamed up around a noodle stall, the bing being the slapping sound of the dough hitting the table. And because it's so rare and so complex, for years it simply didn't exist in Unicode. The master list of every character computers can display. So you couldn't type it, text it, or put it on a digital menu. Restaurants had to draw it by hand or paste in a picture. Only in 20 and 20 did it finally get added. So computers could at last render a single bowl of noodles, a character too complicated for the digital age, invented for a plate of noodles. Proof that even in a world of emojis, some words are just too gloriously complex to type. Want to actually start learning Chinese? Discover thousands of free exercises and more learning content on stacktags.io."
